            <tr class='athing comtr ' id='14336711'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="0"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14336711' href='vote?id=14336711&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335194'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=jasode" class="hnuser">jasode</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14336711">2 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14336711"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="2" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14336711)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00"><i>&gt;Put simply, Eco is telling us to finish what is on our plates before we get up for more. Make sure you master what you have before moving on.</i><p>Everybody has their own angle on how to handle information overload.  That said,  I&#x27;ll offer a different mental model of managing the never-ending reading list.  The &quot;reading list&quot; includes the 50+ open webbrowser tabs of &quot;stuff to read later&quot;, the digital magazines on iPad, the printouts of pdf files (tech whitepapers), and of course, a pile of traditional books.<p>For me, finishing what you already collected before starting on new ones is not optimal.  I don&#x27;t think of a reading TODO as &quot;food&quot; such that you <i>should</i> eat the old food before the new food.  (The old food will expire so it makes sense to consume that first.)<p>Instead, I think of reading as a Priority Queue[1].  I let go of the idea that the various reading piles must be finished in the order I added them to the list.  Many times, a more interesting article or book will go to the top of the queue pushing back a bunch of stuff I added weeks or months ago.  The priority queue is in a perpetual state of being <i>unfinished and constantly adjusted</i>.  That&#x27;s ok.  It&#x27;s the same idea as a priority queue for leisure traveling.  Even if I owned a $75 million Gulfstream private jet, I still couldn&#x27;t travel to all the places I wanted to in my lifetime.  There is no sense of being &quot;done&quot; with my &quot;travel destinations collecting&quot; and I apply that perspective to reading.<p>The above doesn&#x27;t apply to work email inboxes.  I do get anxious if there are unread items there.<p>[1] <a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;en.wikipedia.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Priority_queue" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;en.wikipedia.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Priority_queue</a><span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=14336711&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335194%2314336711">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
